4.1 Introduction
In the last chapter we developed the concepts of position, displacement, velocity and acceleration that are needed to describe the motion of an object along a straight line.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "We found that the directional aspect of these quantities can be taken care of by + and – signs, as in one dimension only two directions are possible.", "fibs": ["aspect"]}
{"text": "But in order to describe motion of an object in two dimensions (a plane) or three dimensions (space), we need to use vectors to describe the above-mentioned physical quantities.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Therefore, it is first necessary to learn the language of vectors.", "fibs": ["language"]}
{"text": "What is a vector?", "fibs": ["vector"]}
{"text": "What is the result of multiplying a vector by a real number ?", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "We shall learn this to enable us to use vectors for defining velocity and acceleration in a plane.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "We then discuss motion of an object in a plane.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "As a simple case of motion in a plane, we shall discuss motion with constant acceleration and treat in detail the projectile motion.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Circular motion is a familiar class of motion that has a special significance in daily-life situations.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "We shall discuss uniform circular motion in some detail.", "fibs": ["uniform"]}
{"text": "The equations developed in this chapter for motion in a plane can be easily extended to the case of three dimensions.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "4.2  Scalars and vectors
In physics, we can classify quantities as scalars or vectors.", "fibs": ["physics"]}
{"text": "Basically, the difference is that a direction is associated with a vector but not with a scalar.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "A scalar quantity is a quantity with magnitude only.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "It is specified completely by a single number, along with the proper unit.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Examples are : the distance between two points, mass of an object, the temperature of a body and the time at which a certain event happened.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "The rules for combining scalars are the rules of ordinary algebra.", "fibs": ["algebra"]}
{"text": "For example, if the length and breadth of a rectangle are 1.0 m and 0.5 m respectively, then its perimeter is the sum of the lengths of the four sides, 1.0 m + 0.5 m +1.0 m + 0.5 m = 3.0 m. The length of each side is a scalar and the perimeter is also a scalar.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Take another example: the maximum and minimum temperatures on a particular day are 35.6 °C and 24.2 °C respectively.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Then, the difference between the two temperatures is 11.4 °C.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "Similarly, if a uniform solid cube of aluminium of side 10 cm has a mass of 2.7 kg, then its volume is 10–3 m3 (a scalar) and its density is 2.7×103 kg m–3 (a scalar).", "fibs": ["uniform"]}
{"text": "A vector quantity is a quantity that has both a magnitude and a direction and obeys the triangle law of addition or equivalently the parallelogram law of addition.", "fibs": ["vector"]}
{"text": "So, a vector is specified by giving its magnitude by a number and its direction.", "fibs": ["vector"]}
{"text": "Some physical quantities that are represented by vectors are displacement, velocity, acceleration and force.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "To represent a vector, we use a bold face type in this book.", "fibs": ["vector"]}
{"text": "Thus, a velocity vector can be represented by a symbol v.  Since bold face is difficult to produce, when written by hand, a vector is often represented by an arrow placed over a letter, say .", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "Thus, both v and  represent the velocity vector.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of a vector is often called its absolute value, indicated by |v| = v.  Thus, a vector is represented by a bold face, e.g.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "by A, a, p, q, r, ... x, y, with respective magnitudes denoted by light face A, a, p, q, r, ... x, y.", "fibs": ["p"]}
