{"text": "4.10  Projectile motion
As an application of the ideas developed in the previous sections, we consider the motion of a projectile.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "An object that is in flight after being thrown or projected is called a projectile.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "Such a projectile might be a football, a cricket ball, a baseball or any other object.", "fibs": ["projectile"]}
{"text": "The motion of a projectile may be thought of as the result of two separate, simultaneously occurring components of motions.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "One component is along a horizontal direction without  any acceleration and the other along the vertical direction with constant acceleration due to the force of gravity.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "It was Galileo who first stated this independency of the horizontal and the vertical components of projectile motion in his Dialogue on the great world systems (1632).", "fibs": ["independency"]}
{"text": "In our discussion, we shall assume that the air resistance has negligible effect on the motion of the projectile.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
