{"text": "This is why this acceleration is called centripetal acceleration (a term proposed by Newton).", "fibs": ["acceleration"]}
{"text": "A thorough analysis of centripetal acceleration was first published in 1673 by the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens (1629-1695) but it was probably known to Newton also some years earlier.", "fibs": ["analysis"]}
{"text": "“Centripetal” comes from a Greek term which means ‘centre-seeking’.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "Since v and R are constant, the magnitude of the centripetal acceleration is also constant.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "However, the direction changes — pointing always towards the centre.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Therefore, a centripetal acceleration is not a constant vector.", "fibs": ["acceleration"]}
{"text": "We have another way of describing the velocity and the acceleration of an object  in uniform circular motion.", "fibs": ["way"]}
